04852nam a22005895i 9780822385165DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223851657 a10.1515/97808223851652doi  a(DE-B1597)554003  a(OCoLC)1154661078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a843/.72211 aLucey, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Misfit of the Family :bBalzac and the Social Forms of Sexuality /cMichael Lucey; ed. by Michèle Aina Barale, Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick, Michael Moon, Jonathan Goldberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (340 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q : 800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction Balzac and Alternative Families -- tChapter one Legal Melancholy: Balzac’s Eugénie Grandet and the Napoleonic Code -- tChapter two On Not Getting Married in a Balzac Novel -- tInterlude Balzac and Same-Sex Relations in the 1830s -- tChapter three Balzac’s Queer Cousins and Their Friends -- tChapter four The Shadow Economy of Queer Social Capital: Lucien de Rubempré and Vautrin -- tEpilogue Vautrin’s Progeny -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn more than ninety novels and novellas, Honoré de Balzac (1799–1850) created a universe teeming with over two thousand characters. The Misfit of the Family reveals how Balzac, in imagining the dense, vividly rendered social world of his novels, used his writing as a powerful means to understand and analyze—as well as represent—a range of forms of sexuality. Moving away from the many psychoanalytic approaches to the novelist's work, Michael Lucey contends that in order to grasp the full complexity with which sexuality was understood by Balzac, it is necessary to appreciate how he conceived of its relation to family, history, economics, law, and all the many structures within which sexualities take form.The Misfit of the Family is a compelling argument that Balzac must be taken seriously as a major inventor and purveyor of new tools for analyzing connections between the sexual and the social. Lucey’s account of the novelist’s deployment of "sexual misfits" to impel a wide range of his most canonical works—Cousin Pons, Cousin Bette, Eugenie Grandet, Lost Illusions, The Girl with the Golden Eyes—demonstrates how even the flexible umbrella term "queer" barely covers the enormous diversity of erotic and social behaviors of his characters. Lucey draws on the thinking of Michel Foucault and Pierre Bourdieu and engages the work of critics of nineteenth-century French fiction, including Naomi Schor, D. A. Miller, Franco Moretti, and others. His reflections on Proust as Balzac’s most cannily attentive reader suggest how the lines of social and erotic force he locates in Balzac’s work continued to manifest themselves in twentieth-century writing and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLiterature and societyzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aSex in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh1 aBarale, Michèle Aina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldberg, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoon, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSedgwick, Eve Kosofsky, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385165zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822